 Fix — run these on Kali

  # Add route so Kali sends 10.0.2.x traffic through this gateway
  sudo ip route add 10.0.2.0/24 via 10.0.1.1

  # Then verify
  ping 10.0.2.10

  To make it permanent on Kali (survives reboot), edit
  /etc/network/interfaces:
  auto eth0
  iface eth0 inet static
      address 10.0.1.10
      netmask 255.255.255.0
      gateway 10.0.1.1
  Or if using NetworkManager, add it in the connection profile.

  ---
  Fix — run these on Ubuntu victim

  # Add route so Ubuntu replies go back through this gateway
  sudo ip route add 10.0.1.0/24 via 10.0.2.1

  # Verify
  ping 10.0.1.10

  To make it permanent on Ubuntu (netplan), edit
  /etc/netplan/00-installer-config.yaml (or whatever file exists):
  network:
    version: 2
    ethernets:
      eth0:
        addresses: [10.0.2.10/24]
        routes:
          - to: 10.0.1.0/24
            via: 10.0.2.1
  Then sudo netplan apply.

  ---
  Why the IIDS itself can ping both — it has direct interfaces on
  both subnets so it doesn't need to route. Kali→Ubuntu traffic
  must go: Kali → 10.0.1.1 (IIDS) → 10.0.2.10 (Ubuntu), and the
  reply: Ubuntu → 10.0.2.1 (IIDS) → 10.0.1.10 (Kali). Both hops
  need their respective routes set.

